http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#com.@value: Allows to represent and associate an annotation format to the different annotations in a document.
Abstract class to represent the arguments of the different  annotation standards.
This class allows to create a composed temporal expression, combining different temporal expressions with the operators OR, AND or NOT.
Class to represent an annotated document.
Annotation of the type EVENT from the TimeML standard
Abstract class of the arguments of the EVENT annotation from the TimeML annotation standard.
Argument CLASS of a EVENT annotation from the TimeML annotation standard.
Argument EID of a EVENT annotation from the TimeML annotation standard.
Argument STEM of a EVENT annotation from the TimeML annotation standard.
A formal representation of an event, such as a frame from Framenet, VerbNet or another semantic repository.
An instance of an event. In the example "he went jogging on Tuesday and Wednesday", there would be one mention but two instances: one on Tuesday and another one on Wednesday.
The textual mention of an event.
The schematic representation of an event.
Annotation from the EventsMatter corpus format. It allows to represent events through annotations of different types (when, what, who, event) sharing an id.
Annotation from the EventsMatter corpus format. It allows to represent the context of an event.
Annotation from the EventsMatter corpus format. It allows to represent the core of an event, meaning what happened.
Annotation from the EventsMatter corpus format. It allows to represent the when an event happened.
Annotation from the EventsMatter corpus format. It allows to represent the who carried out the event.
Identifier of an annotation.
Annotation of the type MAKEINSTANCE  from the TimeML standard. It represents instances of events.
Abstract class of the arguments of the MAKEINSTANCE annotation from the TimeML annotation standard.
Argument ASPECT of a MAKEINSTANCE annotation from the TimeML annotation standard.
Argument CARDINALITY of a MAKEINSTANCE annotation from the TimeML annotation standard.
Argument EIID of a MAKEINSTANCE annotation from the TimeML annotation standard.
Argument MODALITY of a MAKEINSTANCE annotation from the TimeML annotation standard.
Argument POLARITY of a MAKEINSTANCE annotation from the TimeML annotation standard.
Argument POS of a MAKEINSTANCE annotation from the TimeML annotation standard.
Argument TENSE of a MAKEINSTANCE annotation from the TimeML annotation standard.
Represents a temporal expression that repeats over time (e.g. Once a week). In the TimeML standard it would correspond to a SET temporal expression.
Any possible restriction to a sem:Time class.
Annotation of the type SIGNAL from the TimeML standard. It allows to mark up words with a temporal meaning that are not relations, temporal expressions or events.
Abstract class of the arguments of the SIGNAL annotation from the TimeML annotation standard.
Argument SID of a SIGNAL annotation from the TimeML annotation standard.
Argument TIMEX3TemporalFunctionID of a TIMEX3 annotation from the TimeML annotation standard.
Annotation of the type TIMEX3 from the TimeML standard. It allows to represent temporal expressions (dates, times...)

Argument TIMEX3endPoint of a TIMEX3 annotation from the TimeML annotation standard.
Argument FREQ of a TIMEX3 annotation from the TimeML annotation standard.
Argument functionInDocument of a TIMEX3 annotation from the TimeML annotation standard.
Argument MOD of a TIMEX3 annotation from the TimeML annotation standard.
Argument QUANT of a TIMEX3 annotation from the TimeML annotation standard.
Argument temporalFunction of a TIMEX3 annotation from the TimeML annotation standard.
Argument TID of a TIMEX3 annotation from the TimeML annotation standard.
Argument TYPE of a TIMEX3 annotation from the TimeML annotation standard. It can be ft3:DATE, ft3:SET, ft3:DURATION or ft3:TIME.

Argument valueFromFunction of a TIMEX3 annotation from the TimeML annotation standard.
This class represents a temporal expression, meaning a expression representing any temporal reference.
A possible restriction to a sem:Time expression is a temporal relation, such as "before"
Represents the repetition times of a repetitive expression, with an amount (value) and timeunit.
Represents the type of an annotation.
An alternative way to represent the information provided by an Annotation; for instance, a sem:Time would be an alternative value for a  TIMEX3 annotation.

AND relation to combine [TemporalExpressions](http://fromtimetotime.linkeddata.es/ontology/fromtimetotime#TemporalExpression). in a [ComposedTemporalExpression](http://fromtimetotime.linkeddata.es/ontology/fromtimetotime#ComposedTemporalExpression).
The information represented by an annotation.
Connects an Annotation with the AnnotationSchema it implements.

NOT relation to negate a [TemporalExpression](http://fromtimetotime.linkeddata.es/ontology/fromtimetotime#TemporalExpression) in a [ComposedTemporalExpression](http://fromtimetotime.linkeddata.es/ontology/fromtimetotime#ComposedTemporalExpression).

OR relation to combine [TemporalExpressions](http://fromtimetotime.linkeddata.es/ontology/fromtimetotime#TemporalExpression) in a [ComposedTemporalExpression](http://fromtimetotime.linkeddata.es/ontology/fromtimetotime#ComposedTemporalExpression).
Class Instance from GAF, representing an instance of an annotation in text.
Class Mention from GAF, representing a mention of an annotation in text.
Represenents an annotation of any kind, usually NLP.
Represenents an annotation of any kind, usually NLP.
Represents an entity involved in an Event, usually who carried out the action.
Represents an event, in the broadest sense of the term.
This class represents the information of any temporal expression.
Represents a time/date temporal expression  (e.g. Tomorrow at eight o'clock). In the TimeML standard it would correspond to a DATE or a TIME temporal expression.
Represents a duration temporal expression (e.g. Two days). In the TimeML standard it would correspond to a DURATION temporal expression.
Interval representation from the TimeOntology.
Describes the granularity of the repretition in a repetitive temporal expression.

Ontology to support temporal information annotation.
